Part 1: Preparation¶

For this project, I work with a credit card fraud detection dataset from Kaggle, consisting of transactions made by credit cards in September 2013 by European cardholders. The dataset contains only numerical input variables (V1, V2, … V28) which are the principal components obtained with PCA transformation (PCA will the introduced later in this course), due to confidentiality issues. The only features which have not been transformed with PCA are Time (seconds elapsed between each transaction and the first transaction in the dataset) and Amount (transaction Amount).
This dataset contains 284807rows and 30 key features, which are not directly interpretable but contain meaningful information about the dataset.

These graphs illustrate the distribution for each feature and from that we can know which features are useful in distinguishing between fraud and non-fraud transactions and they should be kept. From the above graphs, features V3, V4, V9, V10, V11, V12, V14, V16, V17, V18, V19 are good to use because they have very different distribution for fraud transactions and non-fraud transactions. In contrast, features V1, V2, V5, V6, V7, V8, V13, V15, V20, V21, V22, V23, V24, V25, V26, V27, V28 have similar distribution for fraud transactions and non-fraud transactions, so they are not helpful in differentiating fraud and non-fraud transactions.

Part 2: Single feature model with one Gaussian distribution:¶

I'll start by making a prediction using a single feature of our dataset at a time.

Please note that I only use V features in my model.

a. Fitting regardless of class:

  1. Fit a single Gaussian distribution on a single feature of the full training dataset (both classes) using sklearn.mixture.GaussianMixture when n_components=1.
  2. Compute AUC (Area under the ROC Curve) based on sklearn.mixture.GaussianMixture.score_samples on both the full training set and validation set (including both classes).
  3. Repeat the above steps for each of the features and present your findings in a table.
  4. Find the best 3 features to distinguish fraud transactions from not-fraud transactions based on the AUC of the validation set.
  5. Make a prediction based on a model's scores: If the score_samples is lower than a threshold, I consider that transaction as a fraud. Find an optimal threshold that maximizes the F1 Score of the validation set for each of those 3 features separately.

b. Fitting based on class:

  1. Pick 3 features that had the best AUC in Part 2a.
  2. Compute AUC and F1 score when you fit a Gaussian only on not-fraud transactions (instead of all the transactions).
  3. Compare results from parts 2a and 2b (AUC and F1 score) in a table.

# Part a
# step 1~2
from sklearn.mixture import GaussianMixture
from sklearn.metrics import roc_auc_score, auc

# store AUC
auc_train = []
auc_val = []

for i in range(1, 29): #only use V features in model
  gm = GaussianMixture(n_components = 1, covariance_type = 'full', random_state=0) # gaussian model
  gm.fit(X_train.iloc[:,i].values.reshape(-1, 1)) #fit on single feature

  # AUC on training set
  p_train = gm.score_samples(X_train.iloc[:,i].values.reshape(-1, 1))
  auc_train.append(roc_auc_score(y_train, -1 * p_train))

  # AUC on validation set
  p_val = gm.score_samples(X_val.iloc[:, i].values.reshape(-1, 1))
  auc_val.append(roc_auc_score(y_val, -1 * p_val))

# step 5: find optimal threshold based on F1 score
from sklearn.metrics import f1_score

# store threshold and max f1 score for 3 features
max_tr = []
max_f1 = []

for feature in [4, 10, 14]:
  gm = GaussianMixture(n_components = 1, covariance_type = 'full', random_state=0) # gaussian model
  gm.fit(X_train.iloc[:,feature].values.reshape(-1, 1)) #fit on single feature
  p_val = gm.score_samples(X_val.iloc[:,feature].values.reshape(-1, 1))
  f1_list = [] # store all F1 score
  threshold = [] # store all threshold

  # use method 2 from tutorial2
  for i in [1, 10, 15, 20, 30, 50, 70, 80, 100, 120, 130, 150, 170, 200]:
   tr = sorted(p_val)[i] #We sort the points by probability
   y_pred = [0 if (p > tr) else 1 for p in p_val]
   f1_list.append(f1_score(y_val, y_pred))
   threshold.append(tr)

  max_f1.append(max(f1_list))
  max_tr.append(threshold[pd.Series(f1_list).idxmax()])

For my method of finding optimal threshold, I looped through each possible threshold in a predefined set and computed the corresponding prediction matrix. For each possible threshold, when computing the prediction matrix, I looped through each value in p_val, which takes n since the length of p_val equals to the length of validation set. I also used function sorted() to sort p_val, which takes nlogn on average. Assuming assignment and comparison takes constant time, then runtime for each threshold is n+nlogn. So the total runtime for all threshold is 14*(n+nlogn) since there are 14 possible thresholds. So the complexity of my method is O(nlogn)

Part 3: Multiple feature model with one Gaussian distribution:¶

This part is similar to Part 2, but I will pick multiple features and visually set the number of components.

a. 2D plot:

  1. Pick two features (say, f1 and f2).
  2. Scatter plot (plt.scatter) those features on a figure (f1 on the x-axis and f2 on the y-axis).
  3. Color the data points based on their class (not-fraud blue and fraud red).
  4. Based on my plots, decide how many Gaussian components (n_components) you need to fit the data (focus on valid transactions). Explain.
  5. Fit my Gaussian model on all the data points.
  6. Compute AUC on both training and validation sets
  7. Pick 3 new pairs of features and repeat steps 2 to 6.
  8. For each pair, find a threshold to maximize my validation set F1 Score.
  9. For each pair, plot a figure similar to step 3 and put a circle around outliers based on my threshold (use the code of the similar figure in the tutorial)
In [ ]:
from matplotlib.colors import ListedColormap

# helper function for scatter plot(step 1~3)
def plot_scatter(feature1, feature2):
  colors = ListedColormap(['b','r'])
  classes = ['Non-fraud', 'Fraud']
  scatter = plt.scatter(X_train[feature1], X_train[feature2],marker="x", c=y_train, cmap=colors)
  plt.legend(handles=scatter.legend_elements()[0], labels=classes)
  plt.xlabel(feature1)
  plt.ylabel(feature2)
  plt.show()

# helper function for fiting Gaussian model and compute AUC(step 5~8)
def compute_auc(feature1 , feature2, num_component=1):
  feature_list = [feature1, feature2]

  gm = GaussianMixture(n_components = num_component, covariance_type = 'full', random_state=0) # gaussian model
  gm.fit(X_train[feature_list].values) # fit model

  # AUC on training set
  p_train = gm.score_samples(X_train[feature_list].values)
  auc_train = roc_auc_score(y_train, -1 * p_train)

  # AUC on validation set
  p_val = gm.score_samples(X_val[feature_list].values)
  auc_val = roc_auc_score(y_val, -1 * p_val)

  # F1 score & threshold
  f1_list = [] # store all F1 score
  threshold = [] # store all threshold
  for i in [1, 10, 15, 20, 30, 50, 70, 80, 100, 120, 130, 150, 170, 200]:
   tr = sorted(p_val)[i] #We sort the points by probability
   y_pred = [0 if (p > tr) else 1 for p in p_val]
   f1_list.append(f1_score(y_val, y_pred))
   threshold.append(tr)

  max_f1 = max(f1_list)
  max_tr = threshold[pd.Series(f1_list).idxmax()]

  # plot table
  report_table = {'training AUC':auc_train, 'validation AUC': auc_val,'Max F1 score':max_f1, 'Optimal Threshold': max_tr}
  df_report = pd.DataFrame(report_table, index = [feature1+'&'+feature2])
  return df_report

# helper function for scatter plot with outliers(step 9)
def plot_scatter_outlier(feature1, feature2, num_component=1, threshold = 1):
  colors = ListedColormap(['b','r'])
  classes = ['Non-fraud', 'Fraud']

  # find outliers
  feature_list = [feature1, feature2]
  gm = GaussianMixture(n_components = num_component, covariance_type = 'full', random_state=0) # gaussian model
  gm.fit(X_train[feature_list].values) # fit model
  p = gm.score_samples(X_train[feature_list].values)
  outliers = np.nonzero(p<threshold)[0]

  plt.scatter(X_train[feature1], X_train[feature2],marker="x", c=y_train, cmap=colors)
  plt.scatter(X_train.values[outliers, X_train.columns.get_loc(feature1)], X_train.values[outliers, X_train.columns.get_loc(feature2)],
              marker="o", facecolor= "none", edgecolor="black", s=50)
  plt.xlabel(feature1)
  plt.ylabel(feature2)
  plt.show()

Part 4: Single feature model with two Gaussian distributions.¶

Now I will use two different distributions for fraud and not-fraud transactions.

  1. Fit a Gaussian distribution ($G_1$) on a feature of not-fraud transactions using sklearn.mixture.GaussianMixture when n_components=1.
  2. Fit another Gaussian distribution ($G_2$) on the same feature but for fraud transactions using sklearn.mixture.GaussianMixture when n_components=1.
  3. Compute the score samples ($S$) for both $G_1$ and $G_2$ on the validation set to get $S_1$ and $S_2$, respectively.
  4. Find an optimal $c$ (a real number) that maximizes validation set F1 Score for a model such that if $S_1 < c \times S_2$, the transaction is classified as an anomaly. For example, if $c=1$ we could say that if $S_2$ is greater than $S_1$, ($S_1$<$S_2$) then the transaction is an anomaly (the transaction belongs to the $G_2$ distribution which represents fraud transactions).
  5. Repeat the steps above for all the features. Find the best F1 Score for training and validation.
In [ ]:
# Step 1~4: do it for feature V14

# prepare non-fraud & fraud training set
train_part4 = train.copy()
train_part4 = train_part4.drop(['Time', 'Amount'], axis = 1)  # remove Time & Amount
# non-fraud dataset
train_nonFraud = train_part4.loc[train_part4['Class']==0]

# model 1

# prepare data
X_train_new = X_train.copy()
X_train_new = X_train_new.drop(['Time', 'Amount'], axis = 1)
X_val_new = X_val.copy()
X_val_new = X_val_new.drop(['Time', 'Amount'], axis = 1)

gm = GaussianMixture(n_components = 1, covariance_type = 'full', random_state=0) # gaussian model
gm.fit(X_train_new.iloc[:,:].values) #fit on all feature

# AUC on training set
p_train = gm.score_samples(X_train_new.iloc[:,:].values)
auc_train = roc_auc_score(y_train, -1 * p_train)

# AUC on validation set
p_val = gm.score_samples(X_val_new.iloc[:, :].values)
auc_val = roc_auc_score(y_val, -1 * p_val)

f1_list = [] # store all F1 score
threshold = [] # store all threshold

# best validation F1 score & best threshold
for i in [1, 10, 15, 20, 30, 50, 70, 80, 100, 120, 130, 150, 170, 200]:
  tr = sorted(p_val)[i] #We sort the points by probability
  y_pred = [0 if (p > tr) else 1 for p in p_val]
  f1_list.append(f1_score(y_val, y_pred))
  threshold.append(tr)

max_f1 = max(f1_list)
max_tr = threshold[pd.Series(f1_list).idxmax()]

# training F1 score
y_pred_train = [0 if (p > tr) else 1 for p in p_train]
max_f1_train = f1_score(y_train, y_pred_train)

# results
table1 = {'training AUC': auc_train, 'validation AUC': auc_val,'training F1': max_f1_train, 'validation F1': max_f1, 'best threshold': max_tr}
df1 = pd.DataFrame(table1, index = ['V1~V28'])

from sklearn.metrics import precision_score, recall_score

#prepare test data
X_test_new = X_test.copy()
X_test_new = X_test_new.drop(['Time', 'Amount'], axis = 1)

features = ['V14', 'V10', 'V4', 'V16', 'V11']
gm1 = GaussianMixture(n_components = 1, covariance_type = 'full', random_state=0) # gaussian model
gm1.fit(X_nonFraud[features].values) # fit G1
gm2 = GaussianMixture(n_components = 3, covariance_type = 'full', random_state=0) # gaussian model
gm2.fit(X_fraud[features].values) # fit G2

# score samples on test set
s1 = gm1.score_samples(X_test_new[features].values)
s2 = gm2.score_samples(X_test_new[features].values)

# F1 score on test set
c = 2.8

f1_test = f1_score(y_test, y_pred)
# precision on test set
precision = precision_score(y_test, y_pred)
# recall on test set
recall = recall_score(y_test, y_pred)

# report results in a table
table_test = {'test F1 score': f1_test, 'Precision': precision, 'Recall': recall, 'best c': 2.8, 'Number of Features': 5,
